<paragraph blockId="31.[151,442,720,746]" box="[151,442,720,746]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,442,720,746]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" reason="4">
<taxonomicName authority="Neave, 1910" authorityName="Neave" authorityYear="1910" box="[151,442,720,746]" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Meza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="larea">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,442,720,746]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,285,720,746]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Meza larea</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Neave, S. A." box="[292,442,720,746]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="2 - 86" refId="ref44641" refString="Neave, S. A. (1910) Zoological collections from Northern Rhodesia and adjacent territories: Lepidoptera Rhopalocera. Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London, 1910, 2 - 86, plates I - III, foldout map. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.1910. tb 01885. x" type="journal article" year="1910">Neave, 1910</bibRefCitation>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,790,1570]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Although we have not reared this species, Dollman (unpublished) did, and we include information from his rearing since there is no published information on the early stages for this genus.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,790,1570]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
The food plant at Solwezi, 
<collectingCountry box="[500,588,862,887]" name="Zambia" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Zambia</collectingCountry>
, was ‘kafundula’. Given that Dollman (unpublished) refers to the food plant as ‘a leguminous shrub “kafundula”’, this is probably 
<taxonomicName box="[780,1047,898,923]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Dalbergia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="melanoxylon">
<emphasis box="[780,1047,898,923]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Dalbergia melanoxylon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1065,1175,898,923]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Fabaceae</taxonomicName>
), rather than 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" genus="Balanites" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aegyptiaca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Balanites aegyptiaca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[288,473,934,959]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Zygophyllaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zygophyllales" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Zygophyllaceae</taxonomicName>
), both of which have had this Lunda common name applied (FAO 1988, 
<bibRefCitation author="ICRAF &amp; World Agroforestry Centre" box="[1282,1429,934,959]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" refId="ref43423" refString="ICRAF (World Agroforestry Centre) (2012) AgroForestryTree Database. Available from: http: // www. worldagroforestrycentre. org / sea / products / afdbases / af / index. asp (Accessed 8 May 2012)" type="url" year="2012">ICRAF 2012</bibRefCitation>
) and have similar small leaves compatible with a sketch in Dollman’s notebook and associated with pupal remains in the Natural History Museum, London.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,790,1570]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
Dollman (unpublished) painted the caterpillar life size (
<figureCitation box="[818,931,1042,1067]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="31.[151,249,586,608]" captionTargetBox="[386,1205,316,547]" captionTargetId="figure-549@31.[340,1247,295,564]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 36. Diagram of dorsal view of final instar caterpillar of Meza larea, based on a painting by Dollman (unpublished), on ‘kafundula’ (Dalbergia melanoxylon), Zambia." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5267912" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5267912/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Figure 36</figureCitation>
). The head is dark, with the dorsal half of the face white, two dark streaks on each epicranium extend from the basal edge into this white marking. T1–3 plain dull green. Body dull green; A1–A9 a pair of narrow white dorsal lines which diverge in the anterior and posterior part of each segment, but converge to meet in the middle of each; A1–A8 a narrow white dorsolateral line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,790,1570]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<materialsCitation county="Pupa" location="The" municipality="White" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" specimenCount="1">
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0385994AFFA1FFFF9BFDFD41FEF8BC62:8EF37E87FFA1FFFF9BADFB33FF26BEFB" box="[199,243,1186,1211]" county="Pupa" municipality="White" name="The" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">The</location>
caterpillar lives in a leaf shelter (‘domicile’), but generally pupates on the upper surface of a single leaf, lying along the midrib; the leaf lightly drawn together by a few threads, but by no means closed. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0385994AFFA1FFFF9BFDFD41FEF8BC62:8EF37E87FFA1FFFF9F82FB57FAFCBE9F" box="[1256,1321,1222,1247]" county="Pupa" municipality="White" name="There" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">There</location>
are six of 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0385994AFFA1FFFF9BFDFD41FEF8BC62:8EF37E87FFA1FFFF9BFDFB7BFED9BF43" box="[151,268,1258,1283]" county="Pupa" municipality="White" name="Dollman's" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Dollman’s</location>
emerged pupae in the 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0385994AFFA1FFFF9BFDFD41FEF8BC62:8EF37E87FFA1FFFF996CFB7AFB7ABF42" box="[518,1199,1258,1283]" county="Pupa" municipality="White" name="Dry Early Stages Collection of The Natural History Museum" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Dry Early Stages Collection of The Natural History Museum</location>
, 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0385994AFFA1FFFF9BFDFD41FEF8BC62:8EF37E87FFA1FFFF9FD3FB7BFAC5BF43" box="[1209,1296,1258,1283]" county="Pupa" municipality="White" name="London" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">London</location>
(
<figureCitation box="[1310,1423,1258,1283]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="32.[151,249,1201,1223]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,373,1186]" captionTargetId="figure-352@32.[151,1436,373,1186]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 37. Emerged pupa of Meza larea, on leaf of Dalbergia melanoxylon (?), ex Dollman collection, Zambia (specimen in The Natural History Museum, London)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5267914" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5267914/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Figure 37</figureCitation>
), three on a leaf upper surface as he described. 
<location LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:0385994AFFA1FFFF9BFDFD41FEF8BC62:8EF37E87FFA1FFFF99F6FA9FFD1DBF67" box="[668,712,1294,1319]" county="Pupa" municipality="White" name="The" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">The</location>
leaflets are oval; 
<quantity box="[914,990,1294,1319]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="cm" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3–5cm</quantity>
long x 
<quantity box="[1077,1154,1294,1319]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" unit="cm" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3cm</quantity>
wide; very short petiole. 
<collectingMunicipality box="[151,219,1330,1355]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">White</collectingMunicipality>
waxy powder on silk mat on leaf. 
<collectingCounty box="[626,682,1331,1354]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Pupa</collectingCounty>
distinctive; rounded, quite broad; spiracles inconspicuous, do not protrude; no frontal spike; proboscis projects to a little short of cremaster (
<specimenCount box="[1005,1167,1366,1391]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
); slight lateral flange at base of cremaster; pale brown; whitish speckles all over; dark dorsal dash (elongate longitudinally) on posterior margin of thorax; faint pale dorsal line on abdomen, more or less continuous anterior half, interrupted posterior half; a distinctive white double spot on posterior margin A3 (small) and anterior margin A4 (larger, elongate longitudinally), set in a brown oval (perhaps red in life); black dorsal dash on A8 and two smaller dashes dorsally on cremaster
</materialsCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
